{"text":"Ashwyn, that is a great question.  If the deflections are large, some of the assumptions do not hold true so the solution we obtain may no longer be accurate.  Depending on the desired fidelity of the model, this may or may not be acceptable to you.  Of course, there are many other large assumptions we make when building the model so it is important to realize that this is just a mathematical approximation of the system.  A system with large deflections will likely still display some of the characteristics predicted by the model."}

{"text":"Good observation.  We obtain large deflections in the numerical simulation purely because we used somewhat unrealistic constants for the problem.  If you use realistic values for tension (T) or linear density (rho) you will obtain deflections that are indeed small compared to the length of the string.  However, the unrealistic values we use do not affect the concepts/framework of the solution process, they are merely convenient to numerically simulate."}

{"text":"Matlab has the \"Symbolic Math Toolbox\" that will allow you to do symbolic manipulations similar to Mathematica.  Alternatively, if you have numerical values for your problem then you can do it in Matlab just as easily as Mathematica.  I like to use Mathematica for symbolic manipulation and problem setup/analysis and then use Matlab for the actual numerical solution/simulation of the problem."}

{"text":"Thanks for the kind words.  In general, there is not an equivalent standard form for a 3rd order transfer function.  However, if the third pole of the transfer function is very far away from the other two (in other words much farther in the left half plane) then you can approximate the 3rd order TF with a standard 2nd order TF.  Once you have the approximate 2nd order transfer function, all the material we discuss in this lecture is applicable.  "},{"text":"
"},{"text":"
"},{"text":"
"},{"text":"In addition, every pole has an associated damping ratio (see "},{"text":"https://youtu.be/0tbr4OIufK8?t=829)","videoLink":{"externalVideoId":"0tbr4OIufK8"}},{"text":" and natural frequency (see "},{"text":"https://youtu.be/0tbr4OIufK8?t=1506)","videoLink":{"externalVideoId":"0tbr4OIufK8"}},{"text":".  You can use this if you want to find the damping ratio and natural frequency of a 3rd pole in your system. However the behavior of the overall system will usually be dominated by the two poles that are closest to the imaginary axis."},{"text":"
